<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#00ff00">Originally posted by guitarzan on 01-08-2001 05:53 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Oh.  I'm all over this one.  I just got done doing it no less than 2 hours ago.

Go to bash.  Type:

echo 1 &gt; /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

this turns on ip forwarding in the kernel

then, you edit your ipchains to these read like this:

/sbin/ipchains -A input -j ACCEPT *1 -s 0/0 67 -d 0/0 68 -p udp
/sbin/ipchains -A forward -s *2.0.0.0/255.0.0.0 -j MASQ
/sbin/ipchains -P forward DENY

substitutions: *1 = the device that RECEIVES the internet (i.e. ppp0 eth0) and *2 = the first octect of your windows box's ethernet card ip.

Those three lines mean that for subnet *2.x.x.x, anything coming or going throug *1 is allowed to pass.  

This is a very unsecure gateway.  Very suceptible to hackers.  so if you are conserned with that sort of thing, you'll have to do further editing of your ipchains file to deny certain sorces and destinations of packets.  BTW if you didn't know, the path of ipchains is:
/etc/rc.d/init.d


</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
